design:
Add to workspace deps: portable-pty = "0.8".

New example: crates/phux-server/examples/one_pane.rs
  - tokio current-thread runtime (#[tokio::main(flavor = "current_thread")])
  - Spawn $SHELL via portable-pty::PtySize { rows: 24, cols: 80, ... }
  - Set env: TERM=ghostty
  - Hold PtyMaster, MasterReader, ChildStdin
  - Loop:
      select! {
          chunk = reader.read(&mut buf) => terminal.vt_write(&buf[..chunk]),
          tick = interval.tick() => {
              let grid = pane.capture(&term)?;
              let ops = compute_diff(&prev, &grid);
              eprintln!("frame +{}ms ops={}", elapsed_ms, ops.len());
              prev = grid;
          }
          line = stdin.lines().next() => writer.write_all(line.as_bytes())?,
      }
  - On child exit: print summary and return cleanly

Uses PaneCapture from phux-bc1.1.

No IPC, no protocol framing — that's E3 (phux-byc). Goal here is "real bytes flowing through a real PTY into a real Terminal".

Refactor crates/phux-server/src/grid.rs:

Before: grid::capture(&Terminal) allocates fresh RenderState + RowIterator + CellIterator each call.

After: introduce
  pub struct PaneCapture {
      render_state: RenderState,
      rows: RowIterator,
      cells: CellIterator,
  }
  impl PaneCapture {
      pub fn new() -> Result<Self, CaptureError>;
      pub fn capture(&mut self, term: &Terminal) -> Result<Grid, CaptureError>;
  }

  // Backwards-compat wrapper for one-shot users (tests, diff_spike, future `phux capture` CLI):
  pub fn capture(term: &Terminal) -> Result<Grid, CaptureError> {
      PaneCapture::new()?.capture(term)
  }

Bench: crates/phux-server/benches/capture.rs using criterion. Setup: 80x24 terminal pre-populated with mixed content. Bench measures `pane.capture(&term)` in a hot loop. Assert (via criterion comparison) zero allocations in steady state — use `criterion-perf-events` or trace allocs via `dhat-rs`.

Also: keep crates/phux-server/examples/diff_spike.rs running unchanged after the refactor.
